						               													<description>&amp;ldquo;Defensive line&amp;rdquo; is a game about severe fights which took place in Brest fortress in the beginning of WWII. Each player takes command of one or several units holding their positions in the fortress. The aim is to stand firm, restraining the enemy, as long as it&amp;rsquo;s possible.&amp;#10;Does everybody play for Soviet Army?&amp;#10;Yes, each player is in command of  Red Army unit which can accomplish different military missions. You can win if you exactly coordinate your efforts, which requires high cooperation of players. &amp;ldquo;Defensive line&amp;rdquo; teaches to understand each other at a glance, because altogether you have one goal which you must gain at any costs. Any mistake may lead to the destruction of the whole unit.&amp;#10;What does the move look like?&amp;#10;The units hold several positions when the game starts. At every move the enemy&amp;rsquo;s troops attack the position. Players choose one of the actions (for example, install mines, build fortifications, fire machine-gun etc), according to the situation and the type of enemies. At the end of the move residuary enemy troops attack the fortification.&amp;#10;What does the gameplay look like?&amp;#10;&amp;ldquo;Defensive line&amp;rdquo; is a cooperative game, where the mechanics itself takes the role of opponent. The actions of units are simulated by the cards with tactical decisions. Each unit has 10 cards of a kind. Having played one card you can take another one from the deck without looking. The point of the game is to use tactical cards which are the most effective in particular moments. The victory is possible only when you have the high level of the cooperation of actions: each player must assess the situation and deliberately and precisely use their opportunities. Even when you use an optimal strategy there is a chance of losing or winning with heavy casualties.&amp;#10;Who is &amp;ldquo;Defensive line&amp;rdquo; for?&amp;#10;&amp;bull;    For those who like good collective games.&amp;#10;&amp;bull;    For playing with friends or family.&amp;#10;&amp;bull;    For the journey (game board is composed of the cards).&amp;#10;&amp;bull;    For those who like extraordinary and difficult enough table games. &amp;#10;&amp;bull;    For connoisseurs of balanced tactical games.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
